In article <1994Jun28.191827.7533@princeton.edu>,
Devin Hosea  <0428870@phoenix.princeton.edu> wrote:
>How hard would it be to design a secure phone that would be comprised
>of a PC with a modem, soundcard, and appropriate software?  I am thinking
>that it wouldn't be too tough to string together a public-key encryption
>function that would encrypt small blocks (fraction of a second) of sound
>data at a time, send them in encrypted form by modem, and then have another
>modem receive them, decode, and play.  Given a small-bandwidth (say 4Khz)
>it would seem that this is feasible to do using publicly available encryption
>software and modem technology.  Has anyone tried this?

Yes.  There's been some discussion here about these programs,
at various times.  It's not an easy task, and the sound
quality isn't great, but it's doable.


